<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-317-399  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 317 399.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Feb 6 1989 v8 n3 p18(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DMAC proposals include AST's machines, VP hints. (US TreasuryDept's Microcomputer Acquisition Contract)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Danca, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   AST Research Inc. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    ASTA.andO;Topic:     United States. Department of the TreasuryGovernment ContractsMicrocomputersCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DMAC Proposals Include AST's Machines, VP HintsandM;Computers made by AST Research Inc. may be the choice of some vendors in theTreasury Department's recently closed request for proposals formicrocomputers, an AST official implied in a recent interview.andM;Jerry Moon, vice president of AST's Federal Systems Group, said AST officialshave met with half a dozen system integrators bidding on Treasury'sDepartmental Microcomputer Acquisition Contract (DMAC II).andP;  Treasuryofficials plan to award DMAC II in early summer.andM;Industry sources have said the list of offerors bidding on DMAC II includesFalcon Systems of Bethesda, Md., Sysorex Information Systems Inc. of FallsChurch, Va., SMS Data Product Group Inc. of McLean, Va., GovernmentTechnology Services Inc. of Chantilly, Va., and Tandy Corp.'s Grid SystemsInc. division.andP;  An official from Automated Data Management of Washington,D.C., which holds the current Treasury contract, told GCN last summer thecompany would bid on DMAC II.andM;Moon spoke with GCN before a recent meeting of the Capital PC Users Group.andO;At that meeting AST president Safi Quereshy said deciding on standards formicrocomputer hardware and software should be a business decision, not anemotional one.andM;Quereshy said, &quot;I believe we take ourselves too seriously&quot; in the debatebetween IBM Corp.'s Micro Channel Architecture (MCA) and the competingExtended Industry Standard Architecture (EISA).andP;  AST is a member of the EISAgroup.andM;In the operating system battle between MS-DOS and OS/2, Quereshy predictedDOS will remain for three to five more years and, &quot;OS/2 will take its owntime&quot; becoming a standard.andM;Speaking of the government movement to UNIX, he said, &quot;I feel very confidentabout UNIX now, finally,&quot; because two competing groups are trying to developa standard UNIX.andP;  &quot;Two standards are better than no standard,&quot; he said.andP;  Thetwo groups are the Open Software Foundation and the ATandamp;T Co.-affiliated UNIXInternational.andM;&quot;I believe UNIX will continue to become more popular&quot; as a mainstreamoperating system, &quot;to the dismay of IBM,&quot; he said.andM;Both the PC bus and UNIX standards will be decided by the marketplace,Quereshy said.andP;  However, &quot;the industry is so large that no one standard cansatisfy the needs of the entire industry.&quot;andM;&quot;EISA is a statement of direction&quot; from the nine hardware companies thatsponsored it, he said.andM;He emphasized that the EISA standard only defines input and output methodsand that manufacturers will continue to differentiate themselves throughsystem performance and other features.andM;Quereshy downplayed an early argument in favor of the EISA standard, thatusers want to move add-on boards from older to newer machines.andP;  Not everyadd-on board will move, but many users will transfer network, fax or modemboards back and forth, he said.andM;When manufacturers release EISA machines late this year, they will beexpensive and aimed at high-end, processor-intensive uses such as largedatabases, Quereshy said.andP;  &quot;You will not be able to justify putting an EISAmachine on everyone's desk,&quot; he said.andM;AST late last year introduced two new 80386 computers, including a 25-MHzmodel, and a line of PCs based on the Intel 80386SX microprocessor.andP;  Thecompany also sells 80286-based machines and add-on enhancement products forPCs and Apple Macintosh computers.andO;</TEXT></DOC>